      • getOptionParent

        @Nullable
public IDimpleEventSource getOptionParent()
        The "parent" of this option holder to which option lookup will be delegated for option keys that are not set on this object. Used by IOptionHolder.getOption(IOptionKey).

        Implementors should ensure that chain of parents is not circular!

        By default, the option parent is the same as the event parent.

        By default this returns Node.getParentGraph() if non null, and otherwise returns the value of getEnvironment() (which means that the environment is the default root of the event source hierarchy), but it may be also be set to another value using setEventAndOptionParent(IDimpleEventSource).

        Specified by:
        getOptionParent in interface IOptionHolder
        Overrides:
        getOptionParent in class DimpleOptionHolder
        Returns:
        the parent object or null if there is none.
        Since:
        0.07
        See Also:
        setParentGraph(FactorGraph)

      • getEventParent

        @Nullable
public IDimpleEventSource getEventParent()
        The parent of this object in the event hierarchy or null if at root.

        Unless otherwise noted, this will always have the same value as IOptionHolder.getOptionParent().

        By default this returns Node.getParentGraph() if non null, and otherwise returns the value of getEnvironment() (which means that the environment is the default root of the event source hierarchy), but it may be also be set to another value using setEventAndOptionParent(IDimpleEventSource).

      • join

        public Factor join(Factor... factors)
        Joining factors replaces all the original factors with one joint factor.

        We take the cartesian product of the entries of the tables such that the variables values are consistent. The variable order is determined by taking all of the variables from the first factor in order, then adding remaining variables in order from each remaining factor in turn.

        Returns:
        the new joint factor
        See Also:
        join(Variable[], Factor...)

      • join

        public Factor join(Variable[] variables,
          Factor... factors)
        Merges factors into a single joint factor over the given set of variables.

        Parameters:
        variables - specifies the variables and the order in which they will appear in the new joint factor. This may include variables that are not in any of the specified factors but must not omit any variable that appears in one of the factors nor should it repeat any variable.
        factors - specifies the factors to be merged. If empty, this will add a new uniform factor over the specified variables.
        Returns:
        the new joint factor. If factors has a single entry with the specified variables in the specified order, this will simply return that factor without modifying the graph.

      • initialize

        public void initialize()
        Initializes components of model, and if a solver is set, also initializes the solver.

        Does the following:

        1. Invokes notifyListenerChanged() to reconfigure event notifications.
        2. Initializes non-boundary model variables contained directly in the graph (not in subgraphs) by calling Variable.initialize() on each.
        3. If not Node.hasParentGraph(), initializes boundary variables in the same fashion.
        4. Initializes all model factors contained directly in the graph by calling Factor.initialize() on each.
        5. Initializes nested graphs by invoking this method recursively on each.
        6. Finally, if getSolver() is not null, invokes ISolverNode.initialize() on the solver graph to initialize solver state. The solver is responsible for initializing its component variables, factors and any other state.
        Specified by:
        initialize in interface INode
        Overrides:
        initialize in class Node

        public boolean isForest(int relativeNestingDepth)
        True if the graph is consists of a set of one or more disjoint trees when considering nodes down to the specified relativeNestingDepth of subgraphs.
